time, this Utopian ideal is rarely met: most examples of rugged consumerism conceal rather than foreground the ideological problems to which they respond and thus support or ignore rather than challenge the structures of late capitalist consumerism. By analyzing convergences and divergences between subjective material practices and collectivist politics, Raymond Malewitz shows how rugged consumerism both recodes and reflects the dynamic social history of objects in the United States from the 1960s to the present.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aAmerican literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aConsumption (Economics) in literature. 0aConsumption (Economics)zUnited States. 0aMaterial culture in literature. 0aMaterial culturezUnited States. 4aAmerican Literature. 4aCommodity. 4aConsumer. 4aLibertarianism. 4aMaterial Culture. 4aRepurposing. 4aRugged Individualism. 4alate capitalism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311070398640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804792998zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804792998423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804792998.jpg  a978-3-11-070398-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles